            <h2>Indian National Congress (INC)</h2>
            <p>The Indian National Congress is one of the two major political parties in India. It was founded in 1885 and has played a pivotal role in the Indian independence movement.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="party">
        	<img src="images/bjp.jpg" alt="Bharatiya Janata Party Logo" class="party-logo">
            <h2>Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)</h2>
            <p>The Bharatiya Janata Party is one of the largest political parties in India. Founded in 1980, it advocates for conservative policies and Hindu nationalist agenda.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="party">
        	<img src="images/cpim.jpg" alt="Communist Party of India (Marxist) Logo" class="party-logo">
            <h2>Communist Party of India (Marxist) [CPI(M)]</h2>
            <p>The CPI(M) is a major leftist party in India, advocating for Marxist ideologies. It was founded in 1964 and plays a significant role in various states.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="party">
        	<img src="images/ncp.jpg" alt="Nationalist Congress Party Logo" class="party-logo">
            <h2>Nationalist Congress Party (NCP)</h2>
            <p>Founded in 1999 by Sharad Pawar, the NCP is known for its progressive policies and has a significant presence in the state of Maharashtra.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="party">
        	<img src="images/tmc.jpg" alt="All India Trinamool Congress Logo" class="party-logo">
            <h2>All India Trinamool Congress (AITC)</h2>
            <p>Founded by Mamata Banerjee in 1998, AITC is a major player in West Bengal politics, known for its progressive and reformative policies.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="party">
        	<img src="images/bsp.jpg" alt="Bahujan Samaj Party Logo" class="party-logo">
            <h2>Bahujan Samaj Party (BSP)</h2>
            <p>The BSP was founded in 1984 by Kanshi Ram. It seeks to represent and secure power for the Bahujan Samaj which includes the Dalits, Adivasis, OBCs, and religious minorities.</p>
        </section>
